\begin_layout Standard
Both detectors are Multi Channel Plates which is a rather sophisticated
 kind of electron multiplier.
 The detector is has an area of approximately 10
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset

cm
\begin_inset Formula $^{2}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
CHECK!
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and is very flat within the entire area.
 This very large and flat detector area makes the detector very tollerant
 for ions having sligtly different initial positions in the plane orthogonal
 to the flight directions, since the various ions would make almost identical
 trajectories only sligtly translated.
 The MCP consists of a large number (typically several thousands) of small
 channels coated with a material with low work function material.
 The MCP is heavily biased between the front side and the back side, creating
 a steep voltage gradient across the device.
 When ions hit the surface of the MCP, it will release a number of electrons
 which due to the high voltage gradient will accelerate further into the
 channel.
 Since each channel is very swallow, the electrons will only travel a short
 distance before they again hit the surface and releases even more electrons.
 In this way a single ion will be multiplies into a significant number of
 electrons, how many is heavily dependant on the voltage across the device.
 In our case, we have mounted a rather cheap MCP for the linear detection
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
FIND DATABLAD
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (!!) and a substatially better one, a so-called Z-gap detector, with a
 maximum bias of 5
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset

kV for the reflectron detection.
 Interestingly, the detector is what ultimately sets the limit for the highest
 mass that can be detected.
 It turns out that for heavy ions the detection efficiency drops significantly
 with mass, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Krems2005"

\end_inset

, because the energy of the particle is distributed on a larger and larger
 area which increases the risk that the inital impact of the particle will
 not release a single electron that can be further multipled.
 Since we are among other things also interested in measuring on metal clusters,
 a high mass limit is essential.
 The current Z-gap detector has a nominal maximal detectable mass of 5000
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset

amu, and furthermore, the chamber is equipped with feed-throughs for mounting
 a 15
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset

kV detector if it should be neseccary.
 This should bring detection limit up to approximately 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{6}$
