\begin_layout Subsection
Electronics and data acquisition
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Looking at the wonderfull amounts of stainless steel in figure
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:tof_photo"

\end_inset

, one coulde easily get the idea that all the interesting stuff happens
 inside the vacuum chamber.
 However, nothing could be more wrong, in reallity much of the magic of
 the instrument takes place outside of the chamber in the rather substantial
 amount of electronics that drives the instrument.
 First of all, it turns out that one needs quite a lot of power supplies,
 not only do we need high voltages for the liner potential, 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{liner}$
\end_inset

, also the focus lens, 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{focus}$
\end_inset

, the deflection plate, 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{def}$
\end_inset

, the acceleration plate, 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{pulse}$
\end_inset

, two reflectron voltages, 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{R1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{R2}$
\end_inset

 as well as the MCP detector, 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{D}$
\end_inset

, needs high voltages, all in the range of -4000--4000
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset

V.
 Additionally the four entrance lenses needs a total of five different voltages
 (on lense also acts as a deflector and thus is in two parts).
 For one thing this means that we need quite a lot of power supplies, but
 this is a minor problem, most of the voltages can be supplied by two power
 multi-output supplies, since none of the components uses significant amounts
 of power.
 However, it is also evident that optimizing the system is not espicially
 fun, since the parameter space is extremely large.
 Luckily it turns out that the entrance lenses can be optimized almost independe
nt of the rest of the system, reducing the problem from an 11-dimensional
 problem to a five-dimensional problem and a six-dimensional problem.
 This is however still quite a lot and the initial tuning just to get a
 signal proved to be somewhat of challenge.
 In this situation, it is highly recommended to operate the instrument in
 linear mode since this takes out another to dimensions of the initial optimizat
ion problem.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Ionization
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The parts bought from Jordan of course constitutes the actual analytic instrumen
ts and is what is known as a Orthogonal Acceleration TOF which means that
 the ions to be measured enters the acceleration region orthogonal to the
 direction of flight.
 This is especially well suited to measure on externally generated ions,
 which is actually not the case when measuring on the microreactors, the
 output from the capillary is obviously not ionized when leaving the reactor.
 However, the reason for choosing this type of instrument is, that we originally
 expected to used the TOF as a characterization tool for the two cluster
 source at the department, and these instrument actually do have an ionized
 output.
 This little experimental detail means, that we had to build our own ionization
 source to be able to use the instrument at all.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Optimally all ions will enter with very low energy orthorgonal to the flight
 direction, zero energy in the drift direction and perfectly centered between
 the acceleration plate and the grounded grid imidieatly to the right.
 Of course the ions will not have ideal positon and energy, which will ultimatel
y set the limit of the resolution of the instrument.
 
\end_layout

